african national assembly opposes sanctions against zimbabwe
xinhua news agency , johannesburg , march 18 , the south african national assembly ( oau ) general secretary of the african national assembly ( african national assembly ) , the south african national assembly , criticized the united states , britain , and other western countries in an attempt to force zimbabwe to act in accordance with the wishes of western countries .
in response to the threat posed by western countries to the implementation of sanctions against zimbabwe , the spokesman said : " the zimbabwean people should be under the leadership of the zimbabwean people and should not be decided by the western countries . "
he pointed out : mutual respect for the sovereignty of each country is an international norms that each country must abide by , and the african national assembly resolutely opposes the sanctions imposed on a sovereign state .
the secretary - general said that if the western countries impose further sanctions on zimbabwe , it would not help the zimbabwean people , but would aggravate social unrest in zimbabwe .
he called on the zimbabwean government and opposition parties to work together to overcome difficulties in food shortages and land crisis .
he stressed that only by strengthening unity can we defeat any attempt to split the country .
earlier , the african national assembly issued a statement urging the international community to respect the choice of the zimbabwean people and help them tide over the difficulties .
zimbabwean president robert mugabe was elected again in the presidential election from march 9 to 11 , but the western countries accused the election of having serious shortcomings and the lack of fairness and freedom . therefore , he refused to recognize the election results and threatened to impose further sanctions on zimbabwe .
some western countries have already announced an end to their economic aid to zimbabwe .
prior to the election , the european union ( eu ) has imposed a " clear - cut " sanctions on zimbabwe on the grounds that the zimbabwean government had imposed restrictions on freedom of press and the obstruction of supervision .
